com.inqwell.any

Class Aggregate

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.inqwell.any.AbstractFunc
      • com.inqwell.any.Aggregate
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, Func, NamedFunc, Serializable, Cloneable

    public class Aggregate
extends AbstractFunc
implements Cloneable
    Attempt to aggregate the specified Managed Object instance to the specified Managed Object type with an optional key name.

    Together with Read, this class defines and enforces the rules by which INQ structures are built. These are

    • A managed object instance cannot appear as a direct child of an Array. A Map must be interposed so that the managed object has a name. That name can either be specified as the structure is created or can be allowed to default to a pre-configured value.
    • Array content will be homogeneous, i.e. if a managed object instance has an array ancestor then any aggregation on that instance will apply to all similar instances under the array.

    The Aggregate and Read operations are the way in which INQ structures are built up, in combination with other operations like Filter and so forth. A network of these Func implementations can be assembled to build a working set of data for subsequent use by Func implementations specific to the application.

      • Aggregate

        public Aggregate(Locate instanceFrom,
                 Any descriptor,
                 Any keyName,
                 Any setAlias)
        Aggregate using a specified key of the target. The new instance(s) will be keyed by the instanceAlias parameter or by the descriptor's alias if none is provided. If a set is yielded then this will be known by the setAlias. It is an error if no setAlias is provided and the aggregation results in a set.

      • Aggregate

        public Aggregate(Locate instanceFrom,
                 Any descriptor,
                 Any keyName)
        Aggregate using a specified key in the target. The new instance(s) will be keyed by the descriptor.getName() parameter in their container.

        Note that by not supplying an alias the instancs(s) created by this operation will be known by their descriptor name. This means that any node specification that specifies this part of the locate path will necessarily be tied to the configured descriptor name. In MDA this name is the instance's 'type' (or class) in old money. Any subsequent operations on the structure would then be specifying this type name, which partially defeats the point of MDA in the first place. We thus encourage the use of aliases so that application Funcs can work on structures comprising arbitrary types.

      • Aggregate

        public Aggregate(Locate instanceFrom,
                 Any descriptor)
        Aggregate using a specified key in the target. The new instance(s) will be keyed by descriptor.getName() in their container. The key used will be searched for in the target descriptor from the source instance.
